    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically like the steel handles the pulling forces while the concrete handles the squeezing. what happens if the rebar isn't placed exactly right or if there aren't enough bars in a certain section? does the whole thing just fail suddenly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the rebar isn't placed correctly or if there aren't enough bars in a section, it can lead to a phenomenon called \"bar breakage\" or \"rebar failure\". This can happen when the rebar is subjected to excessive tensile forces, causing it to rupture and lose its tensile strength. It's not a sudden failure, but rather a gradual weakening of the structure over time. In some cases, it can lead to a localized crack or even a complete failure of the concrete, but it's usually not catastrophic – the structure will still hold up, just not as well as it could have. It's like a gash in a girded bridge: the rebar may be compromised, but the overall structure can still support the load, albeit with some additional stress on the surrounding concrete.",
      "source": "target",
